Monday::: November 15::: begins NYU's Trans Awareness Week. Follow NYU LGBTQ+ Center for the full lineup of events and details.

NYU LGBTQ+ Center
November 8 at 12:00 PM ¬∑

November 15 marks the beginning of NYU‚Äôs Trans Awareness Week‚Äîa week-long series of events that celebrates the lives and experiences of transgender::: non-binary::: and gender expansive communities. This week educates the NYU community about how we can collectively uplift trans and non-binary communities and learn more about the issues these communities face. We invite you to join us at our virtual events throughout the week and commit to building a more inclusive community.
.
.
üå∏Monday::: November 15: Black Trans Excellence: An Evening with Raquel Willis @ 6pm - 8pm EST. We invite you to join the NYU LGBTQ+ Center and the Center of Global Spiritual Life for NYU's Trans Awareness Week marquee event: An Evening with Raquel Willis‚Äîa Black trans activist::: award-winning writer::: and media strategist! Raquel will speak about how spirituality and religion have impacted her journey and the importance of centering the experiences::: narratives::: and leadership of Black Trans Women and Femmes in the movement.
.
.
üå∏Tuesday::: November 17: Transcending Love Project and Talk Back @ 5pm - 6:15pm EST. Join the NYU LGBTQ+ Center for an evening of discussion about the 'Transcending Love' portrait series with artist B.Proud and one of the featured couples::: Ja‚ÄôMel Ashely Ware and Alphonso Mills. Photographed by B. Proud::: 'Transcending Love' includes environmental portraits of transgender::: gender fluid::: and gender non-conforming couples::: shining light on their essence and beauty in their full humanity. The couples photographed show an array of relationships::: all with the common thread of people being their true selves and falling in love. The exhibit will be on display in Schwartz Plaza Vitrines 11/12/21 through 02/17/22.
.
.
üå∏Thursday::: November 18: Quench: A Trans Awareness Week Conversation Centering Non-binary Folks @ 12:30pm - 1:45pm EST. What does support and community mean for non-binary people? Join the NYU LGBTQ+ Center for conversations and story sharing about navigating the world as non-binary folks.
.
.
üå∏ Thursday::: November 18: Liberal Studies Global Lecture Series with D‚ÄôLo - The Transformative Power of Comedy: Storytelling as Healing Praxis @ 5:00pm - 6:30pm EST. Actor::: writer::: and comic D‚ÄôLo will speak on The Transformative Power of Comedy: Storytelling as Healing Praxis. The lecture will be introduced by NYU Liberal Studies Professor and Dean Julie Mostov and Assistant Director::: LGBTQ+ Center::: Christopher Griffin::: in discussion with Liberal Studies Professor Sean Eve. In this combined comedic performance and talk::: D‚ÄôLo will demonstrate the power of storytelling as healing praxis for all communities and allies. In asserting and giving voice to our tangled experiences and identities::: we can begin to find healing. D‚ÄôLo::: who has performed/lectured in the U.S.::: Canada::: India::: Sri Lanka::: the UK::: and Germany::: will reveal how this work can be realized transnationally through the use of comedy as a tool for both individual and collective agency and the transformations of trauma into resilience.
.
.
üå∏Friday::: November 19: Intro to NYU LGBTQ+ (Open Session) @ 1:00pm - 2:30pm EST. In this interactive session::: establish foundational knowledge about LGBTQ+ communities::: issues these communities face::: and LGBTQ+ resources at NYU and beyond.

The NYU Ability Project had already been working with the Intrepid Sea::: Air & Space Museum to make its exhibits accessible for people with physical::: sensory::: cognitive::: or behavioral disabilities when the pandemic hit. Safety concerns precipitated by COVID-19 suddenly shifted the focus from tangible (touch) interaction and the use of shared audio guides in the museum::: where visitors could no longer crowd around exhibit labels::: gather in small areas::: or use shared equipment.

The solution? The Bring Your Own Device (BYOD) Mobile Guide::: which allows attendees to use their phones to self-navigate and obtain information about the Intrepid Museum‚Äôs myriad attractions. ‚ÄúWe focused a lot on accessibility of the content::: like recognizing reading level::: thinking about translation to multiple languages::: thinking about audio descriptions for video:::‚Äù says Ability Project director Amy Hurst. She adds that all of it is on a website rather than an application because ‚Äúit‚Äôs much more privacy preserving and also really easy for the staff to update all the content.‚Äù http://spr.ly/6185Jp0QL

üì∑üå±: Have you visited NYU's newest secret garden? This green wall‚Äîalso known as a living wall or vertical greenery system‚Äîin the lobby of @nyupublichealth's new home at 708 Broadway boasts a hybrid irrigation system::: plants that produce high oxygen levels::: and properties that create a unique sense of calm for passersby. If created in an urban environment and on a significant scale::: research suggests that a combination of green roofs and green walls may improve air quality and attenuate noise while promoting the health and well-being of citizens‚Äîsomething to celebrate as we close out Campus Sustainability Month.

‚ÄúNYU faculty research shows that people feel better::: work better::: and study better when they encounter green spaces during their daily lives. It‚Äôs vital to be reminded that nature is not just ‚Äòout there‚Äô in the woods somewhere. We still live in an environment::: even if it‚Äôs a human-dominated one::: and a green wall can remind us of that every time we pass it:::‚Äù says NYUGreen's Cecil Scheib::: NYU's chief sustainability officer.

The creators of the living wall::: an ever-evolving work of art::: selected various blooming plants to provide "pops" of color. Some examples are anthuriums::: the Mona Lisa lipstick plant::: and chocolate columnea. Several species‚Äîincluding aglaonema::: pothos::: and chlorophytum comosum (spider plants)‚Äîare among the plants that::: according to NASA research::: are believed to sequester VOCs::: filter air::: and produce oxygen.

‚ÄúThe inspiration behind our living Green Wall comes from the desire to emphasize the elements of life required to survive and thrive‚Äîearth::: water::: fire::: and air. We hope all who pass by it can benefit from its high oxygen levels:::" says NYU School of Global Public Health Dean Cheryl G. Healton. Learn more: http://spr.ly/6189JTiQP

Referring to people by the pronouns they determine for themselves is basic to human dignity::: but many transgender::: non-binary::: and gender non-conforming people are regularly called by the wrong pronouns::: which causes erasure and marginalization.

PRESS RELEASE:Transformational Gift Leads to Welcome Changes for Grey Art Gallery at NYU - Grey Art Gallery

Grey Art Gallery
October 12 at 8:05 AM ¬∑

Big announcement: The Grey Art Gallery at New York University has received a major gift from Dr. James Cottrell and Mr. Joseph Lovett::: longtime art patrons::: social activists::: and downtown Manhattan residents. The gift includes over 200 artworks from their extensive collection of downtown New York artists from the past 50 years.

The gift will enable the museum to create a named Cottrell-Lovett Gallery as well as the Cottrell-Lovett Study Center::: which will allow visitors to have more direct access to the collection of nearly 6:::000 objects. Once the renovations are completed::: the Grey Art Gallery will be renamed the Grey Art Museum.

The Grey‚Äîwhich closed in March 2020 due to the pandemic‚Äîwill reopen in spring 2022::: before the capital project begins::: with the exhibition "Mostly New: Selections from the NYU Art Collection."

Read the full announcement here:

In honor of Constitution Day (September 17th)

GEORGE WASHINGTON
Deemed the greatest man in the world by everyone
‚Å†
George Washington was famous for his humility::: and was revered as the "Greatest Man in the World" during his timeline according to scholars::: noblemen::: commoners::: and even the King of Britain whom he defeated in battle. He was also the most famous celebrity throughout the world causing people to line-up throughout the countryside just to see him ride past on his horse.
‚Å†
What the 400 British ships didn't see when they sailed into New York Harbor to defeat George Washington and his "ragtag" untrained Continental Army who were fighting for their independence from England's taxes and laws::: was Washington's faith in God and his humility ‚Äï the latter being his most noted characteristic of which people wrote about in their letters and diaries.
‚Å†
Even the other founding fathers agreed that George Washington was the best of them all::: a man with no formal education.
‚Å†
After Washington defeated King George III and his army after eight straight years of battling::: the King acknowledged Washington as being the best man in the world for turning down the opportunity to be ordained King (as many people wanted to see happen)::: and also for handing his devoted army back to the Congress which had never before then been done by a winning war General in order for him to return back to his farm and live out the rest of his life privately at his home although later::: he would be pressured to become the first President of the United States of America in order to continue spreading his noble::: wise and humbling influence.
‚Å†
Washington's army in theory::: should never have won the War for Independence (also called the Revolutionary War)::: but they did even though at times twenty-percent of the army went without shoes or clothing having to endure hot and freezing conditions including walking barefoot through frozen lakes::: cutting their feet on rocks::: and having only to eat "firecake" at times which is flour mixed water prepared in a kettle over fire thus causing many of them to die from starvation and disease when Washington somehow never got sick like the others did.

Over the years::: his army came to believe that Washington survived gunfire and disease because he was ordained by a higher-order like when a thick-mist appeared from nowhere blocking out everything in sight allowing the Continental army to escape an attack so they could regroup and strategize.
‚Å†
George Washington freed all his slaves before he died::: some of them had been inherited from his father during times when even African people were selling their poorest and least educated people under the justification that they weren‚Äôt like humans::: because they were primitive in culture and tradition.
‚Å†
It‚Äôs unfortunate that Washington::: and all the other good people couldn‚Äôt have afforded to purchase all the slaves and give them dignified jobs::: beautiful places to live::: and an educations like many did::: but there were about four million slaves in the end and nobody was rich enough to purchase them all::: especially after the invention of the Cotton Gin which rose America to being the producer of about three quarters of the world‚Äôs cotton.

This amassed some of the biggest fortunes during those times which caused many evil and greedy people to raise the price of slaves to 7 or 8 times higher AND it also posed more danger to slaves overall when talking about abolishing slavery during a time when the people making fortunes from it were never more power hungry who would rather see the slaves killed than become free as proven when they hunted down slaves after they were freed.
‚Å†
Washington's great friend Billy Lee was a black slave that Washington purchased and saved from a potentially horrible fate.
Billy Lee::: rode aside Washington for the 8-years they fought together as a best man and friend.
‚Å†
Fritz Hirschfeld a historian wrote that::: "If Billy Lee had been a white man he would have had an honored place in American history because of his close proximity to George Washington during the most exciting periods of his career. But because he was a black servant::: a humble slave::: he has been virtually ignored by both black and white historians and biographers.‚Äù
‚Å†
George Washington::: top scholars::: innovators::: and the founding father‚Äôs who worked on developing the U.S. Constitution knew that the Constitution was better than them selves::: and that it was the best attempt to give power to the people NOT the evil that will ALWAYS find itself employed in government.
‚Å†
They all knew the slaves must be freed for the Constitution to become all that it was written to be::: but knew a gradual approach to freeing the slaves was the best way to protect them from being killed::: and to plan for their integration into society as free and equal people.

Many Africans came to America of their free will settling first in Portland::: the melting post of vast religions::: languages::: and foreign cultures getting along together and excited to be living and exploring the "new world" of which they didn't originally know was already inhabited by hundreds of Indian tribes::: some unfriendly like the Shawnee who captured and tortured one of Daniel Boone's sons to death::: and were known for scalping the much different looking foreigners.

Many of the tribes were friendly and showed the foreigners how to grow food and navigate through the uncharted and dangerous terrain::: some of them even partnered with the British by guiding them through forestry during the war.

Washington called the Constitution ‚ÄúThe Great Experiment‚Äù and I personally believe it is worth dying for::: just like our Bible is and ancient history which have been removed from public education.‚Å†
‚Å†
GEORGE WASHINGTON QUOTES:‚Å†
‚Å†
‚ÄúThe fate of unborn millions will now depend::: under God::: on the conduct and courage of this army.‚Äù‚Å†
‚Å†
To be prepared for war is one of the most effective means of preserving peace.‚Äù
‚Å†
‚ÄúGovernment is not reason and it is not eloquence. It is force! Like fire it is a dangerous servant and a fearful master. Never for a moment should it be left to irresponsible action.‚Äù
‚Å†
‚ÄúIt should be the highest ambition of every American to extend his views beyond himself::: and to bear in mind that his conduct will not only affect himself::: his country::: and his immediate posterity; but that its influence may be co-extensive with the world::: and stamp political happiness or misery on ages yet unborn.‚Äù
‚Å†
‚ÄúThe time is near at hand which must determine whether Americans are to be fre

Patents and copyrights are stolen in our country
Ivan Str√°nsk√Ω Politics March 29::: 2019
Why do we act like a assembly plant and a herd of useful idiots?
This week I watched the American film Patent Dispute on Czech television. It was a melodrama - the life story of an inventor who::: as an employee of an automotive concern::: invented a simpler solution for a car wiper cycler at Ford. As we know::: courts in the US operate on the basis of jury decisions. I have seen a difficult struggle for patent verification::: with both parties to the dispute proving that the law is on their side. Just before the jury's expected decision::: the night before::: the employer's representative visited the inventor in his home and offered him an out-of-court settlement of $ 30 million (!). Contractually. After consulting with the family::: the dear inventor heroically refused. The next day::: the jury found that the plaintiff's legal claim was justified. And it ruled that Ford was required to pay the applicant $ 10:::390:::000. I do not know how in the United States::: but in our country this would never happen::: even in disproportionat
ely lower amounts. Let me explain why.
In our state::: it is very dangerous to bring into the world not only the idea of a technical solution (even disproportionat
ely more serious than a wiper cycler)::: but also to prove that you have the world's technical first. In order to discourage you from such a label::: the state will first incur high costs for administrative acts and opposition. Then he quite correctly objects to you with similar solutions that already have protection. You have to prove that what you intend to patent has nothing to do with it::: and besides::: it is not only better::: but completely new. As the whole event is of course very complicated and must have the right diction::: you have to hire a patent law expert to process the application and submit the opposition proceedings (in my case it was the renowned patent law office Ziegrroser and partner::: Prague).
If you do not do this and proceed yourself (eg your funds are not infinite)::: then you run the high risk that if your subject matter of the application really has the required novelty::: it is as if you were sending this application directly to competing entities. The Office for Patents and Inventions of the Czech Republic will reject it for formal shortcomings. This puts you in a situation where what you have created in the sweat of your face and in the long days::: weeks::: months::: etc. is thwarted.
Let's say you're with the money and you put it in the right places. You are far from winning! After long delays (usually years)::: the IPO of the Czech Republic will notify you that your world championship has been verified and you will be issued a protection patent document if you pay this issue and annual maintenance fees.
So if you are a new inventor::: you will get a predicate to it. Finally::: you buy a bottle of sparkling wine and celebrate with friends who understand what they have in you::: including a possible wife. (She is happy that the money::: which was not enough::: will be returned to the family.) Whoa.
The Industrial Property Office of the Czech Republic will do what it has to do. He will print the full description of your news in his journal::: including a translation into English. I don't have to elaborate on who and how follows these journals in the sense of industrial espionage. The world's manufacturers in your field will immediately find out the merits of the thing and read it nicely. Then find out how you're doing. Thus::: whether the described subject matter of the invention is protected in states other than yours.
Don't you? Great. They can copy and manufacture it. Do you have? Well::: that's a coincidence! You obviously had a stupid investor who paid for you - protection - because you need "long" money for that. But your stupid investor probably didn't realize that there are so-called modifications to the basic subject of the invention. (It must be saved::: even if it costs millions). The competition will engage their purchased brains and challenge them to bypass your subject matter with a similar modification::: with the playful handling of the evidentiary proceedings in court. (Your stupid investor didn't consider the possibility that he would also protect modifications to your basic idea::: where a certain group of modifications is called a "nest" by patent lawyers.)
Of course::: this costs a lot of money. And so the game of cat and mouse starts. Through lawyers::: you will contact the competition by proposing to transfer the license for their production of your subject matter of the protected invention. They have two paths used. The dead beetle method::: where they ignore your annoying challenges and refuse to negotiate a license. Or do you meet together and they kindly ask what you are asking of them? License fees? Incredibly! Yes::: they read it in the Journal. It is possible that their solution is similar. But they will not provide any payments. Don't you like it? Yes::: please resolve it in court. Prove to us that we are violating your rights. You know::: inventor::: we have a very capable legal representation:::
and we're used to that. In addition::: we have unlimited funding to protect our interests. We will advise you well: you will not win this dispute. What is the next act in this would-be operetta? There are two options. (1) Either clench your teeth with your investor and continue the lawsuit (unlikely). (2) Or your investor will "wrap" you

In a time of seemingly irreconcilable political polarization::: it can be hard to imagine how group and identity dynamics that so often seem to turn toxic could be used to bring us together. But research by NYU's Jay Van Bavel and colleagues suggests that it's actually pretty easy to harness human psychology to build healthy teams. "The minute people are part of a team::: you can observe differences in their brain activity and behavior:::" Van Bavel says. "People are more interested in becoming friends with in-group members and express more empathy when they are in pain. We also find that simply being assigned to a mixed-race team can help overcome our biases‚Äîleading people to automatically feel more positive toward all of their in-group members.‚Äù

Anyone who understands the chemistry of anger can easily control it.

"What is the chemistry of anger?"
There are sixteen chemicals inside us. These chemicals shape our emotions::: our emotions::: our emotions determine our moods and these moods shape our personality. The duration of each of our emotions is 12 minutes. For example::: anger is an emotion. This emotion is caused by a chemical reaction. For example::: our body did not make insulin or it was less than necessary::: we ate too much salt. We didn't get enough sleep or we came out of the house empty stomach. What will happen if we have a chemical reaction inside us? This reaction will increase our blood pressure and this blood pressure will create anger in us. We will erupt but this eruption will only last for 12 minutes. Our body will produce anger-fighting chemicals after 12 minutes and so we will be down in the next 15 minutes::: so if we learn to manage twelve minutes of anger::: then Jim will avoid the ravages of anger.
"Is this prescription limited to anger only?"
No::: we have six basic emotions: anger::: fear::: hatred::: surprise::: pleasure and sadness. All these emotions are only twelve minutes old. We are scared for only 12 minutes::: we laugh for only 12 minutes::: we are sad for only 12 minutes::: we are hated for only 12 minutes::: we are angry for 12 minutes and we are overwhelmed by surprise Stays
Our body normalizes all our emotions after twelve minutes but most of the time we see people all day in a world of anger::: sadness::: hatred and fear. They are not normal all day::: so you look at these emotions like fire. There is a fire in front of you. If you keep pouring a little oil on this fire::: what will happen if you keep putting dry wood on it? This fire will spread and it will continue to burn.
In the same way::: most of us put oil and wood on our emotions instead of quenching them. If we don't manage even during the day::: that passion becomes our long mood and this mood becomes our personality.
Have you ever wondered why so many of us have surprise::: laughter::: hatred::: fear::: sadness or anger on our faces all the time?
The reason is obvious. The emotion knocked on his face for twelve minutes but he did not let it go and so the emotion became surprise::: laughter::: hatred::: fear::: sadness or anger became his personality. He was written on their faces forever. If these people had managed for twelve minutes::: they would have escaped the scourge of a lifetime. They would not have become slaves of any one emotion.
So let's learn how to manage these twelve minutes?
For example::: when I realized that my condition would last only 12 minutes::: I got up quietly::: performed ablutions and started praying. I spent 20 minutes on this process. In those 20 minutes::: my anger also subsided.
So should prayers be offered every time in anger?
"Absolutely not." Whenever I am overwhelmed by an emotion::: I shut my mouth first. I do not utter a word. I go for a walk in the attack of fear::: anger::: sadness and pleasure. I do 'Wudhu'::: I fast for 20 minutes in silence::: I glorify Istighfar::: I try to relax myself by calling the person I like to talk to and try to relax myself by closing my ears and eyes. I go to bed or get up and pray. Twelve minutes pass like this. The storm goes away. My mind comes to rest and I am able to make a decision.
And what do I do if I don't have all these facilities?
I do not open my mouth when the sky falls or the earth cracks
I remain silent and you can be sure that no matter how big the tsunami is::: it cannot cope with the silence of man. He retreats anyway. You too can defeat all the storms of life by remaining silent.
Also::: here are some simple tips to share with you

When you are angry::: leave the scene for some time::: never respond immediately. Stop for five minutes in anger. This will largely control your words. If you are standing::: then sit down. Lying down means changing your position. This will also help you a lot in changing your mood. Drink water immediately because anger is actually fire. ÿ•ŸêŸÑŸéŸëÿß ÿ®ŸêÿßŸÑŸÑŸëŸáŸê) Read it. column1: THANK YOU to the tens of thousands of NYUers‚Äîincluding these staff::: faculty::: and administrators‚Äîwho have done their part to keep our community safe this fall by uploading their required proof of COVID-19 vaccination. If you haven't yet::: it's not too late! http://spr.ly/6181yan4d

We're so excited to welcome students to campus! A Move-In note for those in residence halls: To minimize lines and elevator trips::: and to keep everyone safe::: this year's motto is ONE HELPER::: ONE BIN::: ONE TRIP.

Only one person can accompany a student up to the room at a time. There will be a wrist-band available::: and only those visitors with a wrist-band will be permitted upstairs. Whoever goes upstairs with the student resident must be fully vaccinated or have had a negative PCR test within three days prior to Move-in Day.

NYU provides bins to help students carry their belongings to their rooms; the dimensions are typically about 19 sq ft. We‚Äôd like students to show up with no more belongings than can fit in the bin and be carried by hand in one trip in the elevator. The rest can be shipped. More details: http://spr.ly/6180yQ8gq

Facts::: Accountability and Reflections:

While it is crucial that we all come together in this fight::: we cannot merely move on without learning our history or we will continue to make the same mistakes. As Ronald Reagan said::: ‚ÄúIt is time to restore the American precept that each individual is accountable for his actions.‚Äù

On February 25th::: 2020 during his visit to India Donald Trump promised that a vaccine would be available soon. ‚ÄúNow they have it::: they have studied it::: they know very much::: in fact::: we‚Äôre very close to a vaccine:::‚Äù

On February 28th Trump said at a press conference that the coronavirus will ‚Äúdisappear‚Äù like a ‚Äúmiracle‚Äù. Also in February::: he speculated that warm weather would kill the virus and stop its spread.

On March 4th Trump told Fox viewers that based on a hunch the death rate was a ‚Äúfraction of 1 percent‚Äù.

During that March 4th call with Sean Hannity::: Trump also compared coronavirus with the flu. He mentioned that the flu kills anywhere between 27:::000 and 77:::000 people every year::: implying that coronavirus isn‚Äôt as serious of a threat to public health as Influenza. He also calls Covid-19 "corona flu". He suggested it was fine for people with Coronavirus to go to work::: in sharp contrast to experts. He compared coronavirus to "the regular flu:::" not realizing they are quite different.

On March 7th Trump said that anyone who wants a test for Covid-19 could get one. Many Americans including doctors and patients have proven this was definitely not the case.

On March 10th he told reporters on Capitol Hill that Coronavirus ‚Äúwill go away‚Äù::: not implying months or years from now.

Also on March 10th he said::: "No::: I think the U.S. has done a very good job on testing. We had to change things that were done::: that were nobody's fault. Perhaps they wanted to do something a different way::: but it was a much slower process from a previous administration.
And we did change them. We made the changes. But the testing has gone very well. And when people need a test::: they can get a test.‚Äù (was still a proven lie).

On March 15th::: 2020 apparently he hadn‚Äôt learned by his previous misinformation and that day Trump again contradicted Anthony Fauci's and local health officials‚Äô warnings throughout the U.S.::: at a White House briefing claiming:

‚ÄúIt's a very contagious virus::: it's incredible::: but it's something we have tremendous control of.‚Äù

In recently disclosed videos to Bob Woodward Trump is shown admitting back in February that this was actually a serious threat and much more dangerous than the flu but he didn‚Äôt want to panic you and me. Do you appreciate such life and death information being withheld from you by Big Brother?

Throughout October of 2020 during most of his maskless campaign rallies he proclaimed we had ‚Äúturned the corner‚Äù on the virus but within weeks the rates of the virus and hospitalization
s skyrocketed in most states & the painful lonely deaths are continuing with many hospitals close to capacity.

So I‚Äôm really confused. The GOP in the past has prided itself on holding people personally accountable for their words and actions::: and supposedly being ‚Äúpro-life‚Äù.

Fans say they love that Trump speaks his mind but these quotes are his exact words above and they have been highly inaccurate and knowingly contradictory::: thus risking thousands of American lives. How can you support him & his band of Senate & House enablers::: and look at yourself in the mirror each day?

column1:
Feeling #VioletPride for #NYU2021's John Gargano::: Jr.::: this year's NYU School of Professional Studies undergraduate convocation student speaker who received clemency from former President Barack Obama in 2016. Read more about John's story:

Barack Obama
June 28 at 2:43 PM ¬∑

As President I had the chance to review requests for clemency from people who were incarcerated. It was a task I never took lightly::: since I knew my decision could change the course of someone‚Äôs life.

That was certainly true for John Gargano::: Jr. I granted John clemency in 2016::: and just last month::: he graduated from New York University with an impressive 3.9 GPA and a Bachelor of Science in Leadership and Management Studies.

John grew up on a small vegetable farm in New Jersey. He later moved to Philadelphia after high school and began working various jobs to make ends meet. While there::: he started using and selling drugs and was ultimately arrested and sentenced to 30 years in prison::: despite being a non-violent first-time offender. For the first three years he was incarcerated::: John didn‚Äôt want to talk to anyone. But he eventually vowed that he ‚Äúwould refuse to allow his sentence to break him‚Äù and turned to education to "inspire and restore his hope for the future." He started taking classes through the Ohio University College Program for the Incarcerated::: and helped others prepare for their GED.

After John was granted clemency::: the transition out of the criminal justice system wasn‚Äôt easy. But he credits family and programs like the Coming Home Project at St. Luke‚Äôs Mt. Sinai Hospital in Manhattan::: the Three Strikes Project at Stanford University::: and the Colleges Initiative at John Jay College for helping him make it through. In 2017::: John enrolled at Hostos Community College and graduated with a 4.0 GPA and an Associate's degree in Business Management. In 2019::: he transferred to NYU on a scholarship where he continued to excel in his studies::: participating in their Leadership Fellows program and working as a manager at a restaurant. He also worked to help others who were incarcerated find jobs or pursue higher education.

Last month::: John was selected by his classmates to serve as NYU‚Äôs undergraduate student convocation speaker. Today::: he works as a general manager at one of Chef Tom Colicchio‚Äôs restaurants in New York City and is an advocate for prison reform. John's life is a testament to the power of a second chance‚Äîand I could not be prouder of him.

column1: In the 52 years since Stonewall::: the NYU faculty::: students::: administrators::: and alumni involved with the LGBTQ+ movement have contributed to groundbreaking change and experienced heartbreaking loss. Watch them tell their stories as they reflect on a half century of remarkable social::: political::: cultural::: medical::: and legal transformations that continue to shape our community and our University today:

The uprising that began at the Stonewall Inn::: just blocks away from NYU's Washington Square campus::: in the early hours of June 28::: 1969::: became a turning point in the modern LGBTQ+ movement that is now commemorated in annual Pride marches in the Village and around the world.

The first photo (Courtesy::: of the Municipal Archives::: City of New York) was taken in 1962 to update the ‚Äúproperty card‚Äù for the Village Voice building at the corner of 7th Avenue and Christopher Street::: which then sported a sign advertising the Stonewall Inn. The sign is long gone::: but this stretch of Christopher Street has been re-named Stonewall Place::: and the adjacent park is now a national monument.

In this documentary produced for Stonewall's 50th anniversary::: NYU faculty::: students::: administrators::: and alumni reflect on the groundbreaking change and heartbreaking loss that followed those events in 1969::: and the resulting social::: political::: cultural::: medical::: and legal transformations that continue to shape our community and our University today: http://spr.ly/6188yReti #PrideMonth

NYU Tisch School of the Arts students::: faculty::: and alumni have created "The Haunting:::" an immersive public art installation to be unveiled May 29 at Astor Place Plaza::: commemorating the first anniversary of George Floyd‚Äôs death on May 25.

The Haunting installation features iconography associated with Day of the Dead (D√≠a de los Muertos) and weaves in familiar references for death and mourning from different cultures. The immersive event::: which is free and open to the public from 6:30 to 7:30 p.m. on May 29::: is designed for audience members to move independently through space and interact with performers::: while being immersed in sound and other media. At sunset::: the installation will transform into a candlelight vigil.

‚ÄúRituals are necessary to help remind us where we've been and where we want to go. Many cultures use rituals to keep their struggles::: faith::: and traditions alive and to help them remember. This needs to be our ritual::: every year on May 25::: so we can continue to push for social justice and reform:::‚Äù said James Richards::: co-director of The Haunting and Projection Supervisor at NYU Tisch.

NYU.EDU
NYU Tisch Artists Commemorate Anniversary of George Floyd's Death with Immersive Public Art Installation::: Astor Place Plaza::: May 29

Sheikh Jarrah neighborhood is located on the eastern side of the Old City in occupied Jerusalem. The neighborhood was established in 1956 according to an agreement signed between UNRWA and the Jordanian government.

What is happening today in Sheikh Jarrah is the removal of the Palestinian indigenous people who live in this neighborhood::: turning it into a Zionist settlement::: and the demolishment of Palestinian heritage and culture in this neighborhood.

It is a real catastrophe that the Palestinian people are faced to be displaced and ethnically cleansed by the illegal Israeli forces.

column154:
Sheikh Jarrah neighborhood is located on the eastern side of the Old City in occupied Jerusalem. The neighborhood was established in 1956 according to an agreement signed between UNRWA and the Jordanian government.

What is happening today in Sheikh Jarrah is the removal of the Palestinian indigenous people who live in this neighborhood::: turning it into a Zionist settlement::: and the demolishment of Palestinian heritage and culture in this neighborhood.

It is a real catastrophe that the Palestinian people are faced to be displaced and ethnically cleansed by the illegal Israeli forces.

Sheikh Jarrah neighborhood is located on the eastern side of the Old City in occupied Jerusalem. The neighborhood was established in 1956 according to an agreement signed between UNRWA and the Jordanian government.

What is happening today in Sheikh Jarrah is the removal of the Palestinian indigenous people who live in this neighborhood::: turning it into a Zionist settlement::: and the demolishment of Palestinian heritage and culture in this neighborhood.

It is a real catastrophe that the Palestinian people are faced to be displaced and ethnically cleansed by the illegal Israeli forces.

- A martyr‚Äôs brother's wife has born a baby just a few minutes after he was martyred.

Sheikh Jarrah neighborhood is located on the eastern side of the Old City in occupied Jerusalem. The neighborhood was established in 1956 according to an agreement signed between UNRWA and the Jordanian government.

What is happening today in Sheikh Jarrah is the removal of the Palestinian indigenous people who live in this neighborhood::: turning it into a Zionist settlement::: and the demolishment of Palestinian heritage and culture in this neighborhood.

It is a real catastrophe that the Palestinian people are faced to be displaced and ethnically cleansed by the illegal Israeli forces.

Sheikh Jarrah neighborhood is located on the eastern side of the Old City in occupied Jerusalem. The neighborhood was established in 1956 according to an agreement signed between UNRWA and the Jordanian government.

What is happening today in Sheikh Jarrah is the removal of the Palestinian indigenous people who live in this neighborhood::: turning it into a Zionist settlement::: and the demolishment of Palestinian heritage and culture in this neighborhood.

It is a real catastrophe that the Palestinian people are faced to be displaced and ethnically cleansed by the illegal Israeli forces.

Sheikh Jarrah neighborhood is located on the eastern side of the Old City in occupied Jerusalem. The neighborhood was established in 1956 according to an agreement signed between UNRWA and the Jordanian government.

What is happening today in Sheikh Jarrah is the removal of the Palestinian indigenous people who live in this neighborhood::: turning it into a Zionist settlement::: and the demolishment of Palestinian heritage and culture in this neighborhood.

It is a real catastrophe that the Palestinian people are faced to be displaced and ethnically cleansed by the illegal Israeli forces.

Sheikh Jarrah neighborhood is located on the eastern side of the Old City in occupied Jerusalem. The neighborhood was established in 1956 according to an agreement signed between UNRWA and the Jordanian government.

What is happening today in Sheikh Jarrah is the removal of the Palestinian indigenous people who live in this neighborhood::: turning it into a Zionist settlement::: and the demolishment of Palestinian heritage and culture in this neighborhood.

It is a real catastrophe that the Palestinian people are faced to be displaced and ethnically cleansed by the illegal Israeli forces.

- A martyr‚Äôs brother's wife has born a baby just a few minutes after he was martyred.

- A man who spent a long time in the Israeli jails was deprived of his three sons who were killed by the Israeli raids with no mercy.

column628:
Sheikh Jarrah neighborhood is located on the eastern side of the Old City in occupied Jerusalem. The neighborhood was established in 1956 according to an agreement signed between UNRWA and the Jordanian government.

What is happening today in Sheikh Jarrah is the removal of the Palestinian indigenous people who live in this neighborhood::: turning it into a Zionist settlement::: and the demolishment of Palestinian heritage and culture in this neighborhood.

It is a real catastrophe that the Palestinian people are faced to be displaced and ethnically cleansed by the illegal Israeli forces.

I am Bashar Al-Samour::: at the age of 17. I live in the town of Bani Suhaila::: south of the Gaza Strip. I love farming the land and I was passionate about cultivation because the land is my identity.
Today::: I was not able to plant the crops of this year because the Zionist raids tear my body into pieces. I watered the land with my blood instead of water. So::: my crops will grow up carrying the taste of my blood within them.

My name is Diana Carvajal and I am a professor at Universidad Externado de Colombia. I am astonished at the initiative of this center to promote the talk of former president Alvaro Uribe. The very title "Sustainable Colombia: Politics::: Planet and Democratic Security: A conversation with the president" is a total incongruity and lack of empathy with the current situation in the country.
It bothers me as a citizen and researcher that within this academic exercise you are not considering the before mentioned sensitive issue as well as other voices since there are no other Colombian academics as panelists on this discussion. On the other hand::: you do not take into account information on the damage caused by the government of Alvaro Uribe and the current government of Ivan Duque to human rights and the peace agreements.

I hope in the future your center will discuss Colombian problems with greater and well-informed criteria and out of respect for current conditions::: I think you must cancel this talk.

Join NYU Office of Global Inclusion::: Diversity::: and Strategic Innovation on Tuesday as we take time to reflect on a year's worth of efforts to advance diversity::: equity::: inclusion::: and access::: and look forward to continuing to build a more inclusive university together. events.nyu.edu/event/288883-1

NYU Office of Global Inclusion::: Diversity::: and Strategic Innovation
April 26 at 3:42 PM ¬∑

This has been an incredibly trying and painful year for our New York University communities‚Äîamidst the COVID-19 pandemic and the surge of racism and racist violence that continue to plague the United States and our global community::: we have also experienced arguably the largest::: most global::: and most transgenerational movement for racial justice in history. We have come together to innovate during disruption which has brought forth new challenges along with new opportunities.

During these unprecedented times::: NYU Office of Global Inclusion::: Diversity::: and Strategic Innovation has worked across NYU this academic year to double down on efforts to advance diversity::: equity::: inclusion::: and access. As we do each year::: we are organizing an open space for all NYU community members::: during which Dr. Lisa Coleman::: SVP for Global Inclusion and Strategic Innovation::: will reflect back and charge us to accelerate forward as we create a more inclusive NYU together.

column1: Happy 190th birthday to us! NYU was founded on this day in 1831::: and this Founders Memorial on Schwartz Plaza (just east of Bobst Library) features the only surviving architectural detail from the very first building the University built on Washington Square. It's had quite a journey over the years.  The University Building‚Äîwhich sat on the east side of Washington Square::: where the Silver Center for Arts and Science is now‚Äîwas largely completed by 1835 and dedicated in 1837. Its iconic architectural style was Gothic Revival.  In 1894::: NYU moved the bulk of undergraduate instruction from Greenwich Village to the new University Heights campus in the Bronx. In the same year::: the University tore down the University Building::: preserving this spire‚Äîcomplete with a few "grotesques"‚Äîto install at University Heights in memory of our first home. When NYU sold the Heights campus in 1973::: the Founders Memorial was returned to Washington Square.

column1: It was less than a century ago that Americans confronted the epidemic peak of polio::: a viral disease that attacks the central nervous system. But the country was very different then. ‚ÄúThere was no vaccine resistance‚Äîthe notion of not taking a vaccine because one in a million kids could be hurt by it was ridiculous:::‚Äù says NYU Langone Health's David Oshinsky::: the author of the Pulitzer Prize‚Äìwinning Polio: An American Story. ‚ÄúThere was no belief that the medical community was out to poison or make money off people. There were no TV networks saying the disease was being overhyped by one political party for political gain.‚Äù  In a way::: Oshinsky says::: vaccines are a victim of their own success::: having done their job so well with conditions such as polio that the evidence of what they take care of is gone::: erasing memories of what life was like before them. For that reason::: among others::: it‚Äôs fitting to remember how America successfully‚Äîand collectively‚Äîconquered polio. ‚ÄúIt was all hands on deck:::‚Äù Oshinsky says. ‚ÄúPeople saw what polio was and they were all in it together to make certain that a safe vaccine was produced.‚Äù  Read more in the latest issue of Scope::: NYU's research magazine: http://spr.ly/6186HQWEM

column4: Long post alert: Frustrated graduating senior parent here. Yes::: I know there is a virus. I am an anesthetist and personally care for up to 20 patients a day::: every day::: even with a virus. That being said::: cancelling graduation again seems a bit lackluster in the creative department for such a innovative::: thought provoking::: top tier university especially in light of the fact the the NY Yankees will be playing a game in that same stadium a few days later ...with spectators.  Perhaps the individual schools within the university can hold their graduations there with appropriate distancing?  -Yankee stadium holds 50:::287 fans. -The total number of NYU undergraduate students is: 26:::981. -Divided by 4 (rough estimate) the graduating class should be approximately: 6:::745 students.  -If the students went to Yankee stadium alone (no guests)::: they could have 7 seats between each student! (It could be broadcast for families to see. That seems entirely possible for the number 2 film school in the nation - right?)  -If they each graduate brought 2 guests::: that increases the number of needed seats to 13:::490...divide d into the 50:::287::: allows 3 seats between each group of 3.  Come on NYU::: for a $250:::000.00+ education::: you can try harder and do better. Seriously.

column1: ‚ÄúI was supposed to be doing an internship this semester. Actually::: it was supposed to run from last spring through the fall::: but it was canceled because of COVID. It goes without saying that I was pretty upset about it::: but surprisingly::: another opportunity opened up for me. I‚Äôve had the chance to get involved with a research project called DETER. It‚Äôs run through the Center for Urban Science and Progress and we use vector tracing and 3-D models to track the spread of COVID through urban environments. We‚Äôre focused mostly on New York City because that‚Äôs where we are. It‚Äôs been a really cool thing that popped up that I wasn‚Äôt expecting::: and that wouldn‚Äôt have been there at any other time. I do feel like Manhattan has changed a lot since the pandemic started. Stores close earlier. The streets are a bit emptier. But I‚Äôve also found that the spots in the city that would usually be filled with people are filled with people in a different way. I walked through Times Square the other week and saw at least 30 groups of people filming TikToks on their phones. It‚Äôs like a whole new culture is emerging and people are finding new things to do. They‚Äôre getting outside more and exploring while they have the space and time to do it. Personally::: I‚Äôve been inclined to try new places to eat::: especially when I‚Äôm at Tandon in Brooklyn. I wouldn‚Äôt say I‚Äôm a food connoisseur::: but I do like discovering new foods. I‚Äôll walk around and find new restaurants::: see different areas and different people. The atmosphere changes from block to block. It‚Äôll be sad if the spring semester ends the same way last year did. I‚Äôm really hoping for the whole purple lights::: Yankee Stadium graduation. If that‚Äôs not where it‚Äôs headed::: it‚Äôll be disheartening. I think a lot of seniors coming into this year thought and hoped it would be different.‚Äù  ‚ÄîChristian Hamilton (NYU College of Arts and Science '22) Hometown: Bronx::: New York

column9: Dear Sir or Madam:::  My in English Translated book  In September 1975::: I filed my first application at Magdeburg town hall for permission to leave for West Germany. After many attempts to change my mind::: and following reports by IMs (unofficial informers for the Stasi::: the State Security) that I was planning to defect::: I was thrown in prison four months later. Going on hunger strike a number of times and filing complaints during my time on remand had little effect. Torgau hard labour prison had several Stasi liaison officers on site and many of the inmates were Stasi informers. I consistently refused prison rules::: forced labour and political education (phrase-mongeri ng). I also refused to take part in prison yard military drill. In this way I hoped I might be regarded as ‚Äòintolerable‚Äô and so be deported to the West. Of my four years in prison::: I spent a total of 14 months in strictest solitary detention::: where smoking::: writing and reading was prohibited and mail from home was withheld. At night I had to sleep on a wooden board without a mattress. Lunch was provided once every three days only::: otherwise just two slices of dry bread mornings and evenings. During interrogation I was routinely insulted and referred to as an antisocial pig::: rat::: scum::: parasite::: enemy of the GDR::: criminal::: louse etc. They threatened that I‚Äôd never reach pension age and so would never be allowed to leave for the West. All I wanted was to be free::: but the GDR wouldn‚Äôt let me go. Their laws were inhumane; any kind of resistance or opposition was punished with long prison sentences. Back then I didn‚Äôt yet know that I‚Äôd be imprisoned for a total of four years. If you have ever spent time in a dark::: cold cellar you‚Äôll be able to imagine how horrible it was to be down there for weeks and months at a time. Those in positions of authority during the GDR dictatorship were almost never prosecuted and are today living the good life on undeservedly high pensions::: paid for by the taxpayer. Many perpetrators are still to be found in ‚ÄòDie Linke‚Äô (‚ÄòThe Left‚Äô) political party or even serving in the police or in public office in the eastern part of Germany. column1: ‚ÄúThere‚Äôs definitely been a lot of adjusting going on. All of my lectures are online::: but I do have clinical work every other week and a weekly simulation for another class. For clinical::: I go to NYU Langone Health Orthopedic Hospital. I‚Äôve been lucky not to have any close calls with COVID::: and I think a big part of that is how diligent NYU has been about its own testing program. Clinicals have been smooth overall::: other than having to wear a face shield. It‚Äôs a pain because it fogs up and gets in the way of my stethoscope::: which is really just inconvenient. The simulations have been cut from three hours to an hour and a half::: split between two groups so there aren‚Äôt as many people in a room at one time. I totally understand the reason for it::: but I feel like sometimes I don‚Äôt have enough time to practice the skills I‚Äôm learning. But when that happens I can register for open simulation times to go back in and get more practice. If coronavirus wasn‚Äôt a thing::: I probably wouldn‚Äôt have to put in that extra time::: but I‚Äôm grateful to have the option when I need it. I‚Äôve always been organized::: and it can get pretty hectic trying to keep everything straight::: but if I ever feel like I‚Äôm falling behind::: I reach out to my nursing group to get back on track. I‚Äôm not the best virtual learner. Sometimes it‚Äôs hard for me to feel engaged in lectures. But professors post lecture recordings after class::: so if I ever feel like I missed something important I can watch them and really focus on those parts that I missed or am feeling most nervous about. And since I don‚Äôt have to travel to and from class::: I‚Äôve had time to finally get involved in other things I‚Äôve had my eye on. I joined Nursing Students for Global Health and am currently the vice president.‚Äù  ‚ÄîPaloma Franco (NYU Rory Meyers College of Nursing '22) Hometown: Davis::: California

Slow down::: and challenge yourself to notice: 5Ô∏è‚É£ things you can see right now... 4Ô∏è‚É£ things you can feel or touch... 3Ô∏è‚É£ three things you can hear... 2Ô∏è‚É£ things you're tasting::: and... 1Ô∏è‚É£ thing you smell. During the Fall 2020 semester::: students in the NYU Gallatin School of Individualized Study course ‚ÄúNYC Coastlines::: Past: Present::: and Future‚Äù became the only citizen scientists to collect oyster monitoring data from the Hudson River for The River Project‚Äôs entire 2020 season::: which suffered from a lack of volunteers due to the pandemic.  The course::: which is open to all Gallatin students who need to fulfill a science requirement‚Äîwhether or not they think they‚Äôre ‚Äúgood‚Äù at the subject::: says professor of environmental science Karen Holmberg‚Äînormally includes several field trips to allow students to examine New York City waterways and study the impact of urbanism on the natural environment. But this time::: COVID-19 safety restrictions led Holmberg to ‚Äúpull apart the syllabus at the seams and rebuild it:::‚Äù scrapping visits to the Coney Island MTA yard::: the Cornell oyster hatchery::: and the NYC Archaeological Repository in favor of an enhanced outdoor experience with The River Project::: among other real-world opportunities for data collection.  The River Project::: part of the Hudson River Trust::: has previously welcomed Holmberg‚Äôs classes to tour its lab::: but this time invited the students to take part in actual oyster monitoring over the course of several weeks instead. The oysters::: which are on wire meshes attached to pier pilings::: are tagged with a number and all living oysters were measured and weighed. The health of the oysters are examined each month to determine the health of the Hudson River.  ‚ÄúStudents enjoyed getting muddy and understanding the monitoring process by collecting data about the mortality and growth of the oysters:::‚Äù Holmberg says. ‚ÄúAn artist in our group took silt from the oysters and created a drawing of an oyster. We were outside and still masked and distanced but it was a different level of freedom. The students did such a great job with the data collection that they were invited back for the following month.‚Äù  In addition to oyster monitoring::: students also visited Red Hook in Brooklyn to collect data for The Citizens‚Äô Water Quality Testing (CWQT) project. Traveling by ferry instead of subway or car gave students a greater connection to the water they were studying‚Äîand an opportunity to sample Steve‚Äôs key lime pie::: a neighborhood favorite::: as a reward for making the trek in the cold rain.  One student reflected on the experience::: stating::: ‚ÄúI think the project exemplifies how science is all around us::: not just in a lab. While we are going to explore our findings in a scientific manner we are also engaging with the waterfront which has given me a new appreciation for the city's coastline. I also have a new appreciation for field scientists::: who have to endure harsh conditions to continue projects and discoveries.‚Äù  That‚Äôs always been Holmberg‚Äôs hope for the course‚Äîthat it will nurture in students a better understanding of how embedded in the natural world we all are::: especially in an era of climate change and sea-level rise::: all while reinforcing the idea that science starts with close observation::: which can be done everywhere and by anyone. ‚ÄúCitizen science is crucial as it broadens the data collected for scientific understanding but also gives increased understanding to the environmental issues we face:::‚Äù she says.

column1: "After a year of difficulties and turmoil and sorrow::: I thought::: as I am sure many of you did::: that 2021 would be different. I didn‚Äôt delude myself that all our problems would be solved ‚Äî there are too many::: and some are too large. But I allowed myself the belief that we might leave the worst behind::: usher in a period of righting the most egregious wrongs::: avoid the worst ignominies::: and begin to replace untruth with facts and divisiveness with understanding.  And then came January 6::: 2021.  In the worst desecration of American democracy perhaps any of us have known::: a violent mob ‚Äî incited by a steady diet of lies and stoked grievances::: indifferent to the will of American voters::: unconcerned about the tenets of democracy ‚Äî stormed the Capitol::: disrupted the work of Congress in duly certifying the election of a new president::: and upended the peaceful transition of power that has been a centuries-long::: cherished foundation of American political life.  It was a preposterous::: unimaginable scene::: like something from a novel picked up in an airport bookshop that we can enjoy reading because of its implausibility. This has been a heartbreaking::: damaging::: and disgraceful ordeal.  There are so many questions that will emerge from this day: how did we end up with leaders so willing to put their own personal::: political interests ahead of the nation‚Äôs welfare? How has political courage become so rare::: that elected officials are willing to let corrosive lies and mistrust stand when they have every reason to know better? How have we allowed our civic dialogue to become so debased that we are nonchalant about dangers of political extremism? How can we explain the passivity of law enforcement towards a throng that breached the Capitol and threatened Congress::: much less reconcile it with the aggression previously shown towards peaceful protesters challenging injustice and oppression::: many of whom were people of color? How resilient is our democracy::: really?  On this unnerving day::: I console myself with four thoughts. First::: that notwithstanding its January date::: I will consider this one of the final incidents of 2020 rather than one of the opening events of 2021. Second::: I hope ‚Äî indeed::: I believe ‚Äî that the Constitutional traditions and democratic institutions that drew me to American citizenship will::: along with common sense::: reassert themselves::: and that this episode will ‚Äî by casting the stakes in such sharp relief ‚Äî prove to be the death knell for this destructive brand of politics::: as the Army-McCarthy hearings were in their time. Third::: that regardless of today‚Äôs awfulness::: there will be a peaceful transition of presidential power two weeks hence. And fourth::: that I am lucky to pass the coming period of reflection and correction in the company of a community of scholars and learners committed to truth::: peace::: mutual respect::: inclusion::: and true justice.  I share your sense of unease and discouragement. In response::: I say: stay strong and steady::: and stay true to our collective values. Take courage from one another‚Äôs comradeship. In the weeks and months and years to come::: this country will need us at our best more than perhaps ever before.  Sincerely::: Andrew Hamilton"  NYU.EDU A Message from NYU President Andy Hamilton on Today's Events

column1: Bye bye::: 2020! üéâüéâüéâ

‚ÄúThis semester has been exhausting. I feel like my days are longer and my classes drain so much more out of me because I‚Äôm not physically there to connect with other students. Since it‚Äôs all through a screen::: it feels like it‚Äôs just me and the professor. There‚Äôs no horizontal connection happening. And I think that‚Äôs been the theme. A lot of things that students are involved in::: both extracurricular and academical::: are much more labor intensive despite being virtual. Even though I don‚Äôt have to physically go to my classes::: the hours that I spend in front of a computer screen are so lengthy that by the time I wrap up my average weekday around 7 p.m.::: I‚Äôm completely spent. One of the reasons I came to NYU in the first place was to connect with other students and broaden my network. Some professional development programs have done a good job of adapting to the virtual environment. But things like on-campus recruiting::: which is a huge part of being a Stern student::: are completely remote now. I was fortunate enough to secure a job for after graduation::: but there are many students::: especially sophomores and juniors::: who aren‚Äôt getting the same facetime with employers that they would have otherwise. Even though I have a job lined up::: it was uncertain for a long time. I didn‚Äôt know how it was going to work or how I could efficiently network with recruiters. When I was studying away at NYU Washington::: DC::: last spring::: I saw the impact COVID had on the economy. I watched the numbers fall in real time. For a business student::: or any student who‚Äôs professionally oriented::: it was completely unsettling. But we looked for ways to find hope. Stern‚Äôs alumni program coordinated a speaker series with students who graduated in 2008 and 2009. They came and spoke about their experiences with a recession market and shared their wisdom about what to do when it feels like the sky is falling.‚Äù  ‚ÄîSpencer Asch NYU Stern Undergraduate College '21 Major: Business and Political Economy Hometown: Whitehouse Station::: New Jersey

column1: ‚ÄúI‚Äôm still here and trying my best. That‚Äôs really all I can do. Right now::: it seems like you can either orient yourself toward the future or just try to make the best of the present. For me::: it‚Äôs orienting myself toward the future because the present situation is rough. I‚Äôm looking forward to the spring not really because anything‚Äôs going to change::: but because I‚Äôll be done with law school applications. I‚Äôve had a lot of time to focus on them this semester::: and I‚Äôve gotten a lot more responses than normal when I‚Äôve reached out for help with personal statements and scholarships. It‚Äôs been a really stressful process::: so I‚Äôm glad I‚Äôve had more time to dedicate to it. I‚Äôve also continued to be the community service committee chair and a mentor in the Academic Achievement Program. I run a mentorship and tutoring program called World Changers. It‚Äôs a partnership with a high school in the Bronx. We connect virtually with students every Friday after school to help them in any way we can. We aren‚Äôt just helping them write their college essays. It‚Äôs just as important to talk with them about mental health::: because we‚Äôre all struggling. We talked with the school‚Äôs directors over the summer::: and they really emphasized that a lot of their students were sharing that they don‚Äôt feel any type of hope and don‚Äôt feel like anything‚Äôs ever going to be normal again. In talking with other mentors::: we realized that we wanted them to be productive::: but also that we understand that something is going on in all our lives and we can‚Äôt just expect people to act like everything‚Äôs normal. One week::: we did a workshop where the high school students wrote personal statements. So many of them talked about having a family member pass away from COVID::: or COVID hurting their mental health. It‚Äôs affected everyone::: and it‚Äôs important to give a space where people can spend time talking about what‚Äôs really going on.‚Äù  ‚ÄîCasandra Delgado (NYU Gallatin School of Individualized Study '21) Concentration: Criminalizing Narratives: Advocacy::: Public Policy::: and Law Hometown Detroit::: Michigan

column1: ‚ÄúIt‚Äôs frustrating being a Global Liberal Studies student and not being about to have that global experience. Especially this year. As a junior::: I‚Äôm supposed to be studying away::: learning to cook in Italy or on a beach in Abu Dhabi. If you had told me a year ago that it would be this way::: I would‚Äôve said ‚Äòoh::: heck no!‚Äô But we have to make the best of it::: and maybe next Fall I can study away. At the beginning of the semester::: it seems like people were frustrated because it felt like the University was being too strict. But this is an unprecedented situation. They don‚Äôt have a guidebook for colleges to follow during a pandemic. Getting tested once a week and filling out the daily screen is tedious::: but what‚Äôs the alternative? Yes::: there‚Äôs a pandemic going on::: but when you zoom out::: people are quite literally fighting for their lives in so many ways. When I look back in 10 years::: I don‚Äôt want to think ‚Äòoh::: that was just a horrible semester. I just sat inside and did my classes.‚Äô I want to be able to look back and say that I went out and voted in one of the most important elections of my lifetime. That I attended a protest. That I did everything I could. I want to be able to say I didn‚Äôt waste a year or lose any time. I‚Äôm afraid of that::: especially living in New York. I feel like it goes by so fast. This moment won‚Äôt last forever::: so I look at everything that‚Äôs happening and::: rather than drowning myself in pity::: I realize that people are fighting for their lives. So much change is happening in the world::: despite the current circumstances. I want to be a part of that change::: even if it‚Äôs not part of what‚Äôs considered a ‚Äònormal‚Äô college experience.‚Äù  Rida Ali Global Liberal Studies::: 2022 Ashburn::: Virginia

column1: Last week::: NYU Tisch School of the Arts Drama students presented "Everybody" (directed by Candis C. Jones) and "Forgive Us::: You‚Äôre Dying" (Joshua William Gelb)::: two digital productions inspired by the fifteenth century morality play "Everyman." But rather than simply performing inside their Zoom screens‚Äîlike many remote productions have done during New York‚Äôs theater shutdown‚Äîstudents pushed the platform's boundaries for storytelling during a pandemic.  Using the same sophisticated software traditionally employed by designers to create visuals for physical and live performance::: students experimented with dynamic staging that isn‚Äôt stuck in a grid format. They learned the new skill of ‚Äúbox choreography:::‚Äù where an actor‚Äôs Zoom box enters and exits the screen::: or collides and overlaps with other Zoom boxes to create shared worlds within the play or evoke specific feelings in the audience. Director Joshua William Gelb‚Äîwho has been covered in The New York Times and New York Magazine for converting his closet into a tiny experimental theater venue‚Äîlikened the experience to ‚Äúacting in a CGI spectacular:::‚Äù where the challenge is to find the right eyeline to communicate with other remote actors and replicate the feeling of being in shared space.  Student designers also used digital manipulation to expand how plays are typically performed inside a physical theater. Using green screens::: they borrowed from surrealist artists like Frida Kahlo and Salvador Dali to create intricate and visually arresting virtual sets that helped integrate isolation and the remote process into the action of the story.  In "Forgive Us::: You‚Äôre Dying:::" shown in these images::: actors brought their characters to life in miniature tarot card environments and introduced surprising effects such as shuffling the cards. The staging was set up ahead of time::: and although the finished production looked as though it had been recorded and edited::: the play was actually performed and streamed entirely live.

column1: ‚ÄúIt‚Äôs a whirlwind thinking about the spring semester. I‚Äôll be closer to being a senior and things will get more serious::: so I‚Äôm a bit nervous. I‚Äôm not sure if I‚Äôll go back to New York for classes. I‚Äôve found all these great opportunities outside school that I can take advantage of being fully remote. I would love to continue to do that because I know there‚Äôs more out there that I can do in the spring. One unexpected upside of being remote is that professors can invite guests to come to class so much easier on Zoom than they can in person. In my film class::: my professor invited Todd Phillips to talk with us about his films. My journalism class brought in writers from the New York Times and the Washington Post who shared how their work takes them through life. I feel like I‚Äôve had a lot of freedom this semester::: so I‚Äôve been trying to take advantage of it while staying safe. I‚Äôve been able to meet people::: take gigs::: and be part of productions while taking a full course load. It‚Äôs great because I‚Äôm able to work on a job and then bring my experience back to class where I can ask questions and share information. I‚Äôve realized that I can learn and work at the same time. Even though it‚Äôs a bit strange::: I‚Äôve found that if I think about online learning in the right way::: it opens up a whole new set of doors on how I can work effectively and use this time well. I think the main issue is not physically being in class. That leaves it up to me to find motivation and ways to be hands-on. When I‚Äôm on campus::: I go to class and I‚Äôm assigned a crew. I‚Äôm in a studio and there‚Äôs a camera::: a mic::: and a script. I can‚Äôt do that right now::: so I have to do it myself. As soon as the pandemic hit::: I had to adapt. It‚Äôs been an involuntary test of how ready I am to be an independent adult and a working professional in the film industry. Filmmaking isn‚Äôt the same as it used to be. It‚Äôd be so easy to say ‚ÄòOh::: it‚Äôs shut down. There‚Äôs nothing else.‚Äô But there‚Äôs so many opportunities for me to be a creative filmmaker and visual storyteller during this pandemic. One of my favorite musicians says something like ‚Äòlimitations are the most freeing thing ever.‚Äô That‚Äôs become my credo. I‚Äôm limited::: but I can be resourceful. I have to be creative and I still have to deliver.‚Äù  Kirill Bykanov NYU Tisch School of the Arts and Arthur L. Carter Journalism Institute '22 Hometown: Moscow::: Russia Studying from: Wilton::: New Hampshire

column1: ‚ÄúI don‚Äôt like to quit things. I know a lot of people say that::: but once I‚Äôm committed to something::: I‚Äôm going to finish it. This semester has been a testament to how committed I am to getting my degree. Doing it at a time like this::: in these conditions::: has shown me how much I care and want to keep pushing through. I took two classes last summer that were supposed to be on campus. With everything that happened::: they got moved online and I took them from home. It wasn‚Äôt a great experience for me because it‚Äôs already hard for me to stay focused::: and everything being online made it even harder. I spent a lot of time weighing the pros and cons and talking with my parents and friends about coming back to campus. I knew this semester was going to be intense in terms of my course load and the classes I‚Äôm taking for my major. I‚Äôd worked so hard over the summer to get on track with my classes::: so the idea of taking the fall off was like ‚Äòwhat am I going to do instead?‚Äô NYU had a plan in place::: so I felt like coming back to campus was the best decision for me. I wouldn‚Äôt say the semester‚Äôs been great::: but I‚Äôm definitely appreciative that I can be here. The workload has been crazy::: but I‚Äôm making the best of it because::: at the end of the day::: I really want to be here. I feel like::: among students::: everyone has bonded together because we‚Äôre all going through the same thing. Even taking classes online::: everyone has been really willing to connect::: exchange numbers::: and get some form of contact. It‚Äôs a ‚Äòhelping each other‚Äô mindset.‚Äù  Sofia Monfiglio (NYU Tandon School of Engineering '23) Hometown: San Francisco::: California

column1: The COVID-19 pandemic has presented not only challenges but also incontrovertible lessons. Science matters. How we treat the environment matters. Understanding racial and societal disparities matters. Public policy matters. Evidence-based research matters. Too often these topics are dismissed as merely "academic." But in the past nine months we have seen over and over that they can mean the difference between suffering and flourishing::: between death and life. In this profound and historic time::: members of the NYU community have treated patients on the front lines::: advised policymakers::: researched vaccines and treatments::: sent personal protective equipment where it's most urgently needed::: helped to improve testing techniques and understand the spread of the virus::: creatively reconfigured teaching and training::: and advocated for the most vulnerable among us. A new special edition of the NYU Alumni Magazine::: How We Faced the Crisis::: chronicles these stories: http://spr.ly/6189H8QVZ

498 of 502 of student-athletes on 23 teams‚Äîthat's 99.2% overall‚Äîregistered to vote thanks to a relay-style challenge started by NYU Steinhardt School of Culture::: Education::: and Human Development student Janean Cuffee and NYU Women's Basketball:  New York University October 9::: 2020 at 6:52 AM ¬∑  It started with a text to her teammates: You have 48 hours to register to vote. ‚ÄúI told them to like the message to show that they‚Äôd seen it::: and then to text back confirmation when they‚Äôd registered:::‚Äù says Janean Cuffee (NYU Steinhardt School of Culture::: Education::: and Human Development ‚Äò21). Then::: once all the NYU women‚Äôs basketball players had registered::: it was the men‚Äôs team‚Äôs turn. After that came men‚Äôs and women‚Äôs soccer::: with the same rules‚Äî48 hours to register::: no excuses‚Äîbefore the challenge was passed to baseball and softball and so on.  Janean::: a shooting guard::: had been tapped by her coach Meg Barber to coordinate this relay approach to getting 100% of NYU athletes registered to vote by around October 5‚Äîthe deadline to be able to participate in the November 3 election in several states‚Äîand she jumped at the chance. ‚ÄúThere are multiple studies showing that college students actually vote the least::: which is totally shocking because what we‚Äôre being taught is to use our voice:::‚Äù she says. ‚ÄúAt NYU we have people from all across the country::: and I think it‚Äôs important for them to be heard in every state::: regardless of who they vote for.‚Äù And unlike a mass email::: a personal text from a peer‚Äîwith a hard deadline‚Äîappealed to athletes‚Äô commitment to discipline and teamwork.  The effort grew out of conversations with Janean‚Äôs teammates::: who‚Äôd been meeting weekly (on Zoom) to discuss how they could collectively make change in the wake of the summer‚Äôs protests around racial justice. And it also fits in to a broader mission to combat inequality through education::: which has motivated many of the opportunities she‚Äôs pursued while at NYU.  An applied psychology major::: Janean held jobs as a mentor and athletics coach at Harlem Children‚Äôs Zone::: a writing tutor for high school students working on their college admissions essays::: and a research assistant for NYU‚Äôs Researching Inequity in Society Ecologically Lab::: which focuses on health and legal system disparities for traditionally marginalized youth and families. Through the organization Uncommon Schools::: which runs a network of charter schools for low-income students in New York::: New Jersey::: and Boston::: she completed a summer teaching fellowship::: and after graduation will teach in her own classroom while working toward a master‚Äôs in education.  ‚ÄúAll of the jobs I've had are centered toward helping people in general::: and specifically focused on making equality for underprivileged communities and children:::‚Äù Janean says. And she wants to emphasize that voting is another way of doing that.  ‚ÄúWe have a big election coming up:::‚Äù she says. ‚ÄúVoting is your right. Use it.‚Äù  Make your voting plan with NYU Votes: nyu.edu/nyu-votes

column1: NYU Steinhardt School of Culture::: Education::: and Human Development September 24::: 2020 at 1:43 PM ¬∑  "The Office of Equity::: Belonging::: and Community Action at NYU Steinhardt::: in collaboration with NYU Metro Center::: Steinhardt Student Affairs::: the Undergraduate Student Government (USG)::: and the Graduate Student Organization (GSO)::: will be holding space in response to the troubling grand jury decision not to indict the officers responsible for the murder of Breonna Taylor. We feel with you the elastic pain::: continuing trauma::: and numbing fatigue that yet another verdict has been handed down reinforcing the devaluation of Black womxn‚Äôs lives.  We support and are committed to efforts to ensure that we are part of the solution that finally dismantles systemic intersectional racial injustice and violence. Indeed::: we need a commitment::: plan::: and structure to make it happen. But we also need to hold space for each other::: to give people room to feel and be seen and heard.  In the coming months::: the Office of Equity::: Belonging::: and Community Action will roll out new programs and services::: which will include::: among other things::: a new Social Justice Resources page where you will find resources useful in our struggle for social justice::: and a list of equity trainings our office will make available to our community.  Transforming a broken system is a big undertaking and will require the involvement of many people to make an impact. It is important to stress the need to embed our culture and all we do with social justice strategies to dismantle structural racism and its many antecedents::: without simply adding more tasks. In the spirit of systemic change::: we want to utilize the strength of our office to enable change. This means that::: in addition to offering resources and trainings::: our office will set up people-powered committees to galvanize our collective genius and community cultural wealth::: to hold us accountable::: and to help create the change we wish to see.  More immediately::: we want to provide a space for you to both hear from one another and be heard::: where you can share and discuss your stories::: feelings::: and experience with others. This space will be to discuss Breonna Taylor::: humanize the value of Black (femme) lives and countless other victims of police brutality::: the recent and current protests::: and related topics.  Justice for Breonna Taylor: A Listening and Healing Space for the Community: Friday::: September 25 at 5:00pm to 6:30pm Please register for the event (https://bit.ly/33XEoLF) or email steinhardt.equity@nyu.edu for more details."

column1: #TBT: As our community continues to grapple with how COVID-19 has changed university life::: we've been looking through the NYU Archives to see how previous generations of students::: faculty::: and staff met other historic moments of upheaval and uncertainty.  A hundred years ago::: as they looked forward to graduation::: rising seniors from the Class of 1920 contemplated how the conflict that would come to be known as World War I had shaped their college experience. "We have flourished during::: and in spite of the war:::" wrote one class representative in the NYU yearbook. ‚ÄúAnd so we stand today at the close of three of the most trying years the civilized world has ever known::: conscious of what we have achieved and justly proud of it::: but preferring to be judged by those who know us rather than judge ourselves.‚Äù

Fifty years ago this week::: a group of NYU students and local LGBTQ+ activists staged a sit-in at the Weinstein Residence Hall subbasement for five days in protest of the University‚Äôs cancellation of an LGBTQ+ dance. Eventually::: the police were called in and put an end to the protest. Out of this event arose many advances in LGBTQ+ recognition at NYU::: as well as the creation of S.T.A.R.‚ÄîStreet Transvestite Action Revolutionaries‚Äîone of the first trans advocacy groups.  Photos by Diana Davies. Manuscripts and Archives Division::: NYPL The New York Public Library::: 1970. Accessed via the Digital Collections.
